   <text>
      <body>
         <div>
            <head>15.10.1881 Samstag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49097">Ascot.</placeName> 15 October. 1881 Saturday</p>
            <p>We were to go to Hampton court, where we were to lunch with <persName key="1027">M<hi rend="ul.2">
                     <hi rend="sup">r</hi>
                  </hi> Hodgekin</persName> today but as it hailed and rained we went to <placeName key="49050">London</placeName> instead. In the train we thought we would have our
               dinner so just as we had taken out our things we arrived at a station and heard the
               guard crying &#x201e;All change for <placeName key="49050">London</placeName>&#x201c; so out we had
               to get holding our bread in our hands but we managed to finish our dinner in the
               other carriage. We got to <placeName key="49050">Waterloo</placeName> at 2 o&#x2019;clock
               whence we drove to the <orgName key="66953">Savoy theatre</orgName> in a bus to see <name type="work" key="36567">Patience</name>
               <note type="reg">
                  <persName key="128">Sullivan</persName>
               </note> a most intensely utter play in the aesthetic line. It is chiefly written in
               an incomprehensibly tatoo language. There were some good jokes as when Bunthorne says
               &#x201e;Then a sentimental passion of a vegetable fashion must excite your languid spleen.
               An attachment à la <persName key="8101">Plato</persName> for a bashful young potato&#x201c;
               &#x201e;By hook and crook you try to look both angular and flat&#x201c; But the best is when the
               Mayor says in a most agonizing fashion after standing in a very intensely aesthetic
               attitude &#x201e;I wonder what the inner Brotherhood usually recommend for cramp&#x201c; The
               colonel also sharply remarked that to be aesthetic was to be angular and flat After
               the theatre we walked down Piccadily without a poppy or a lily as the people in the
               play did. We had chocolat Grange not mango and got home at about 7½. I am growing
               intense </p>
         </div>
